|BIO I am a huge Stranger Things fan. I have bingewatched all seasons and episodes a couple of times and am patiently but impatiently waiting for other seasons. Here is some trivia about me: LIkes: Computer Programming
column10: drawing
column11: dancing
column16: looking up at the sky and searching for cancellations and studying planets. Dislikes: Slow Internet
column18: abuse and bullying
column19: and being ignored (especially on purpose) Favorite seasons: Summer and Spring. Sometimes Fall and Winter because of Halloween and Christmas. That is a summary of me
column20: thank you for visiting my page. :) Have a good day! Favorite Characters Will Mike Eleven (El) Steve|

|The Hawkins National Laboratory seems to conduct unusual experiments." lends undue doubt to something we know to have happened. Prefer nonjudgmental language. "Martin Brenner is pure evil." is a judgement by moral standards that are not shared by the entire readership. Verifiability {{ShortcutSTW:VER}} Verifiability on {{SITENAME}} is the readers ability to check [[Stranger Things Wiki:Citationcited sources]] that directly support the information in an article. All objective information in {{SITENAME}} must be verifiable
column10: but because other policies and guidelines also influence content
column11: verifiability does not guarantee inclusion. Verifiability
column13: is one of the fundamental requirements for inclusion in {{SITENAME}}; truth
column15: is not a substitute for meeting the verifiability requirement. No matter how convinced you are that something is true
column16: do not add it unless it is verifiable. Information supported by actual broadcast episodes
column18: are considered implicitly verified when (and only when) the episode is actually broadcast for the first time. It must be possible to attribute all information in {{SITENAME}} to reliable
column19: published sources that are appropriate for the content in question. However
column20: in practice it is only necessary to provide inline citations for quotations and for any information that has been challenged or that is likely to be challenged. Appropriate citations guarantee that the information is not [[Original researchoriginal research]]
column21: and allow readers and editors to check the source material for themselves. Any material that requires a citation but does not have one may be removed. For help on adding citations
column22: see [[Stranger Things Wiki:CitationCiting sources]]. This policy applies to all objective material in the mainspace (Episode Pages
column25: and Production Pages). In terms of Spoilers and Commentary pages
column26: text and pictures from articles may be copied into the site ONLY IF the work referenced has attribution. For photos and images
column27: proper licensure and source is expected. Just being "out there on the Internet" does not make a photo free to use on this Wiki! Original research {{ShortcutSTW:OR}} The term "original research" (OR) is used on {{SITENAME}} to refer to materialsuch as facts
column29: and ideasfor which no reliable
column30: published sources exist. This includes any analysis or synthesis of published material that serves to advance a position not advanced by the sources. To demonstrate that you are not adding OR
column31: you must be able to cite reliable
column32: published sources that are directly related to the topic of the article
column33: and directly support the material being presented (and as presented). The prohibition against OR means that all material added to articles must be attributable to a reliable published source
column34: even if not actually attributed. The verifiability policy says that an inline citation to a reliable source must be provided for all quotations
column35: and for anything challenged or likely to be challengedbut a source must exist even for material that is never challenged. That "Paris is the capital of France" needs no source
column36: because no one is likely to object to it and we know that sources exist for it. The statement is attributable
column37: even if not attributed. Despite the need to attribute content to reliable sources
column38: you must not plagiarize them or violate their copyrights. Articles should be written in your own words while substantially retaining the meaning of the source material. Wikia Policies There are very few policies which apply across all Wikia. These can be found on the Central Wikia at [[Wikia:Category:Policy]]. Other policies for this Wikia are usually decided by the wiki community in a consensus vote. Copyright Except where otherwise specified

|The Article Layout Guide shows how articles should be structured and organized on the wiki. This page will explain the organization of different types of articles
column10: as well as how to properly add content to each section. Character Pages Page Layout Character Pages should more or less follow this layout: History Background Season Personality Relationships Familial Character Name NonFamilial Character Name Appearances Memorable Quotes Behind the Scenes Trivia Gallery References Some of the sections included on the above list are optional. Some characters may even need additional sections depending on the information. History Here
column11: the characters actions throughout the series will be described. All events
column12: excluding those that are included in the Background subsection
column13: should be written in the order that they happened in the story. All information should be recorded as it was presented in series. No speculation or opinions should be present in this section. The events should focus on the character whose page you are writing it for. The events should also be written inuniverse and in past tense: Correct: Mike played Dungeons & Dragons with his friends in the basement. Incorrect: In the first episode
column14: Mike is playing Dungeons & Dragons with his friends in the basement. Background This section consists of events that took place in the characters life before the start of the series. Events that are shown in flashbacks should be included in this section. For some pages
column15: this subsection may be divided into different sections. For example
column16: Elevens background is split into Birth and Early Life and Psychokinetic Training. Some characters may not have this subsection due to there being no information about their past. Season Here is where the events that took place in the current timeline of the story. This section is usually what takes up a majority of the article. Be descriptive. Dont overly summarize events. Make sure to include all events. Even if the character only appeared in the background in a scene
column17: it should be included. Personality Here the qualities of the characters personality will be described. This section may sometimes be called Personality and Traits. Its not enough to just say a character is brave. Give some examples of the characters bravery. The characters likes and dislikes can be noted here. Any other traits
column18: characteristics
column19: and mannerisms can also go here. Relationships Here is where the characters relationships will be described. Basically
column20: summarize the characters interactions. This section usually has two subsections: Familial This can also include adopted and surrogate relationships. NonFamilial this includes all other relationships that are not part of the characters family. Friends
column23: and other relationships should go here. The relationships should be written mostly from the perspective of the character youre writing it for. Only notable relationships should be described here. While Holly Wheeler is Mikes sister
column24: not much has been shown of them interacting
column25: so Holly should not be included in this section on Mikes page. One common problem with writing this section is that some interactions between characters may have different meanings and interpretations to other people. As a result
column26: it is sometimes easy to get carried away with personal opinions. Please avoid this as much as possible and instead focus on how the characters relationships were meant to be depicted in the story. If at any point this section becomes too lengthy
column27: then it should be moved to a separate page. Appearances This is where the characters episode appearances are noted. Usually
column28: this section only consists of the Season Appearance templates. For more information
column29: please view the Templates section below. Memorable Quotes Here notable things said by the character will be listed. The quotes should be placed with bullet points and have quotations marks. The Quotes should be important and have impact. Fanfavorite lines can go here. Behind the Scenes Behind the Scenes is a section for "realworld" facts. Facts about casting and the characters creation should be written here. This section should be written in paragraphs
column31: it should not be written from an inuniverse point of view. Trivia Trivia is a collection of interesting
column32: often little known facts about the character. All facts should be written in bullet points. This section can include: Observations made about the character by observing background clues or hints present in dialogue. Facts revealed about the character in interviews
column33: or any other official source. Acknowledgment of fan reactions and fan theories. This section is also one of the few sections where speculation is somewhat acceptable
column34: as long as it is made clear that it has not been confirmed. Gallery Galleries are to display interesting images. In this case
column35: the gallery will display images of the character during interesting or major situations. The basic code for a gallery:|

Sections Synopsis A brief summary of the season. The official synopsis written on the Netflix website should be written here. Plot summary A condensed description of the seasons plot. column24: such as schedules and filming of particular scenes. Special effects Any details about how the seasons SFX were accomplished. Music Details about the music used in the season. Can include details about both the original score

column26: such as editing. Marketing Advertising for the season. This section mainly consists of the seasons trailers. Other Pages While all other page types on the wiki dont have specific layouts that should be followed

edit_content: |It is highly possible that an article has far too many images that they overshadow the significance of the article. The editors here should strive for a tasteful array
column10: rather than a garish smorgasbord of images. Such displays should be curated to the most significant
column11: impactful

column10: the wiki will run more smoothly and look more polished. For the purposes of this guide
column11: it will be assumed that whoevers reading it at least knows the basics of editing. If not
column12: there are plenty of [[community:Help:Tutorialtutorials]] available over at [[community:Community_CentralCommunity Central.]] Asking more experienced users
column13: as well as the wikis staff
column14: is also a good way to learn. Page Layout The usual layout for a character page should be like this: Introduction History Background (optional) Season Personality Relationships (may be a separate article) Family Friends Enemies Other Appearances Memorable Quotes Behind the Scenes (optional) Trivia (optional) Gallery (may be a separate page) References (optional
column15: but preferred) Please keep in mind that this is the usual layout for a Character page. Pages about locations
column17: etc. may have different layouts. Introduction The articles introduction is basically what introduces the reader to the subject. A good way to write this section is to summarize the subjects storyline throughout the series. History While you summarized the subjects role in the introduction
column18: here you will go into more detail. This section will usually be the majority of the article. Background|

edit_content: |The purpose of this page is to serve as a guide for new contributors to the wiki. This way
column10: the wiki will run more smoothly and look more polished. For the purposes of this guide
column11: it will be assumed that whoevers reading it at least knows the basics of editing. If not
column12: there are plenty of [[community:Help:Tutorialtutorials]] available over at [[community:Community_CentralCommunity Central.]] Asking more experienced users
column13: as well as the wikis staff
column14: is also a good way to learn. Articles Content: One majority of the wikis content will simply be derived from the source material
column15: while the other majority will be from interviews and other official statements from the cast and crew. Any information on this wiki must be verifiable and come from official sources. Those sources must be cited. All information must be officially revealed. No information from leaks or untrustworthy sources will be permitted on the wiki. This wiki focuses on canon. This is not a place for fanon content
column16: with the only exception being for use on User profiles. Speculation
column18: or opinions should be absent from main article sections. If something is ambiguous in the series
column19: then it should be ambiguous on the wiki. Minimal speculation should only be applied when it is necessary and must be somewhat supported by hints present in canon. Writing: Keep in mind when writing for articles that the main purpose is to record information. The writing should be comprehensible
column20: but not too overly complicated or fancy. Formal language should be used. Avoid using any slang or overly casual tones. Articles should be written from a neutral point of view (NPOV) even when writing for antagonists or describing events that could be seen as malicious. Please avoid simply tacking sentences on to the ends of paragraphs. Instead
column21: try to integrate the sentence where it belongs in the paragraph
column22: or even rewrite the paragraph to include the information. Tense: Episode pages should be written in present tense. Character pages
column23: as well as most other pages
column24: should be written in past tense. Exceptions to this are trivia sections
column25: and any other section where present tense is necessary. Citing Sources Sources are extremely important to the wiki. They let readers know that the information they are getting is confirmed and reliable. References must come from reliable sources. Reliable sources can include: Official interviews with the cast and crew. Posts made by any of the shows official social media accounts. Posts made by any of the cast and crews social media accounts. Videos posted by the official Netflix Youtube channel
column26: or other credible channels. Videos of the cast at comic con panels. (While posted by unofficial sources
column27: they still contain official statements.) When citing a reference
column28: the content must be place between tags. For example: It is extremely important that the reference links to the original source. They should also have the name of the website where the source was published
column29: as well as the date it was published. A typical reference should follow this format:|

Creates subsection headers for galleries. When or When Not to Create an Article While its true that the wikis purpose is to be a place to house and obtain information
column17: its important to remember that this is the Stranger Things Wiki. All articles on this wiki must be related and relevant to [[Stranger ThingsStranger Things]]. However
column18: that does not mean that every single character or item mentioned in the series is necessarily important enough to get their own page. The series also often has references to reallife people and media
column19: especially those that inspired it. While these references are interesting and should definitely be mentioned
column20: that doesnt mean they warrant their own article. Relevancy: This will be the main factor when figuring out if a subject should have its own page. Was the subject relevant to the show/story? Did it play a major role
column21: or was it just mentioned in a passing line of dialogue? The [[sensory deprivation tank]] deserves its own article because it played a vital role in the story; it was how Eleven entered her mental void where she made contact with the Monster
column22: opening the rift to the Upside Down. Meanwhile
column23: the [[Atari]] Will receives for Christmas doesnt need a dedicated article as it was only mentioned in passing and is not important to the overall story. Information: Is there enough information on the subject to warrant an article? If only two or three sentences can be written about the subject
column24: odds are it shouldnt have an article. Integration: While the subject may not require its own article
column25: that doesnt mean it shouldnt be mentioned at all. If the subject is related to another bigger
column26: more important topic
column27: then it can be integrated somewhere on that topics article either as its own section or a subsection. Combination: Sometimes
column28: if there are multiple similar subjects that alone do not have enough information
column29: they can be combined into a single article. The "[[Cultural influences and references]]" and "[[Minor Characters]]" articles are good examples of this. [[Category:Wiki guidelines]]|

column11: but its not really official (or entirely clear for that matter). I think the community needs to agree to a standard and stick to it. I think articles about things that exist "inside" the shows universe (characters
column14: etc.) should be written in the past tense. Were writing about events from 1983
column15: after all. Writing in the present tense reads like a plot summary

edit_content: |/ Color palette notes updated July 2019 One of the "tricks" of an allredandblack design is figuring out a way to distinguish between the red of the "existing link" and the red of the "new link" all while keeping the redonblack contrast ratio high enough for people of varying visual acuities able to read the page. / .pageStranger_Things__Sample_Wiki_Season_3 a.new
column10: .pageStranger_Things__Sample_Wiki_Season_3 a.new:visited { color:ffb7b7!important; } .pageStranger_Things__Sample_Wiki_Season_3 a:hover { color: ffa0a0; textdecoration:none; } / General background qualities Making the blending stop at the top

edit_content: |{{TlcAbout}} is a commonly used [[wikipedia:WP:Hatnotehatnote template]] on Wikipedia
column10: and should be placed at the top of an article
column11: linking the reader to other articles with similar titles or concepts that they may have been seeking instead. The template has several formats
column13: a parameter can be added to the {{TlcAbout}} template for use at the top of a section. When using this parameter
column14: the wording in the template changes to specify that it is being used in a section: {{TlxAboutUSE1}} → {{AboutUSE1sectionyes}} {{TlxAboutUSE1}} → {{AboutUSE1PAGE2sectionyes}} {{TlxAboutUSE1USE2PAGE2}} → {{AboutUSE1USE2PAGE2sectionyes}} {{TlxAboutUSE1USE2PAGE2andPAGE3}} → {{AboutUSE1USE2PAGE2andPAGE3sectionyes}} {{TlxAboutUSE1USE2PAGE2other uses}} → {{AboutUSE1USE2PAGE2other usessectionyes}} For more options
column15: find "{{TlfAbout}}" in the text below. For reference
column16: see [[wikipedia:Wikipedia:hatnotehatnote]] and documentation below. {{Hatnote templates}} [[Category:Disambiguation and redirection templates]] [[Category:Hatnote templates]]|

|Description This template is used to insert descriptions on template pages. Syntax Add at the end of the template page. Usage On the Template page This is the normal format when used: TEMPLATE CODE {{documentation}} If your template is not a completed div or table
column10: you may need to close the tags just before is inserted (within the noinclude tags). A line break right before can also be useful as it helps prevent the documentation template "running into" previous code. On the Template/doc page Normally
column11: you will want to write something like the following on the documentation page: Description This template is used to do something. Syntax Type somewhere. Samples results in... {{templatenameinput}} Use any or all of the above description/syntax/sample output sections. You may also want to add "see also" or other sections. Note that the above example also uses the [[Template:T]] and [[Template:T/piece]] templates.|

|This template produces formatted text
column10: following the guideline for a [[WP:HATNOTEhatnote]]. : {{hatnoteExample hatnote text.}} Broadly speaking
column11: a hatnote should answer a readers question (maybe preemptively): Am I on the right page? Function This template is primarily used to add a correctly formatted hatnote to a page. Often
column13: this is a disambiguation link at the top of article pages. It places an HTML block around the text entered as its only argument
column14: which provides standardized formatting (contents are indented and italicized in most displays); it also isolates the contained code to make sure that it is interpreted correctly. This template is also used as the "metatemplate" for additional specialized disambiguation link templates; see [[:Category:Hatnote templates]] for a list. The template does not automatically create links of any kind. Links and other desired formatting must be explicitly added
column15: using normal [[Help:Wikitextmarkup]]. Usage ; Basic usage: &123;{hatnotetext}} ; All parameters: &123;{hatnotetextextraclassesextra classesselfrefyescategoryno}} Parameters This template accepts the following parameters: the hatnote text. (required) any extra CSS classes to be added. For example
column16: the {{tsee also}} template adds the classes boilerplate seealso. if set to "yes"
column18: "true" or "1"
column19: adds the CSS class "selfref". This is used to denote selfreferences. if set to "no"
column23: suppresses the error tracking category ([[:Category:Hatnote templates with errors]]). This only has an effect if the first positional parameter (the hatnote text) is omitted. Example → {{hatnoteExample hatnote text}} Errors If no hatnote text is supplied
column24: the template will output the following message: {{hatnotecategoryno}} If you see this error message
column25: it is for one of four reasons: No parameters were specified (the template code was instead. Some parameters were specified
column26: but the hatnote text wasnt included. For example
column27: the template text instead. The hatnote text was specified
column28: but that text contains an equals sign (""). The equals sign has a special meaning in template code
column29: and because of this it cannot be used in template parameters that do not specify a parameter name. For example
column30: the template code . You tried to access [[Module:Hatnote]] directly by using instead. If you see this error message and are unsure of what to do
column31: please post a message on [[Template talk:Hatnote]]
column32: and someone should be able to help you. Pages that contain this error message are tracked in [[:Category:Hatnote templates with errors]]. Technical details The HTML code produced by this template looks like this: The code is produced by [[Module:Hatnote]]. {{ifeq:{{SUBPAGENAME}}sandbox [[Category:Hatnote templates ]] [[Category:Crossreference templates]] }}|

column10: an [[Gateinterdimensional gateway]] was opened at [[Hawkins National Laboratory]]. As a result
column11: an alien biological growth originating from the mysterious [[The Upside DownUpside Down]] began to spread through and consume the lower levels of the lab. By October 1984
column12: a series of interconnected tunnels had formed as a result of the Upside Downs intrusion. The tunnels appear to have stemmed from the Gate before branching out and spreading under the whole of [[Hawkins]].]]}} [[Category:Main Page templates]]|

edit_content: |{{HeadermaintextFEATURED ARTICLEsize30barwidth355}} {{Headermainrighttext[[Demogorgon (species)DEMOGORGON (SPECIES)]]size23barwidth0}}[[File:Demogorgon Chapter Eight.jpgleft190pxlinkDemogorgon (species)]]Demogorgons are predatory creatures originating from the [[Upside Down]]
column10: an alternate dimension. Demogorgons obey the malicious [[Mind Flayer]]
column11: and make up part of his hive mind. Under his influence
column13: violent and have limited intelligence. In 1983
column14: a [[The Demogorgonfully grown Demogorgon]] set foot in [[Hawkins]]
column15: Indiana after a [[Gategateway]] to the Upside Down was accidentally opened. This Demogorgon was eventually defeated and destroyed
column16: but not before it could inflict damage upon the human world. [[Will Byers]]
column17: a rescued victim of the Demogorgon
column18: became a vessel for the Mind Flayer. Somehow
column19: Wills possession allowed the Mind Flayer to unleash a swarm of adolescent Demogorgons upon Hawkins. {{Center[[Demogorgon (species)]]}} [[Category:Main Page templates]]|

edit_content: |{{HeadermaintextFEATURED ARTICLEsize30barwidth355}} {{Headermainrighttext[[The Upside DownTHE UPSIDE DOWN]]size23barwidth0}}[[File:UpsideDownS2.pngleft210pxlinkThe Upside Down]]The Upside Down is an alternate dimension existing in parallel to the human world. Most
column10: if not all
column11: flora and fauna present in the dimension are linked together in a hive mind controlled by the [[Mind Flayer]]
column12: essentially forming an enormous superorganism. A key component of this hive mind was a species of humanoid predators
column14: which originated from the dimension. {{Center[[The Upside Down]]}} [[Category:Main Page templates]]|

edit_content: |{{HeadermaintextFEATURED ARTICLEsize30barwidth355}} {{TextcolorRedW}}{{TextcolorOrangeI}}{{TextcolorYellowL}}{{TextcolorGreenL}} {{TextcolorBlueB}}{{TextcolorVioletY}}{{TextcolorRedE}}{{TextcolorOrangeR}}{{TextcolorYellowS}} [[File:Will S2.pngleft170pxlinkWill Byers]]William "Will" Byers
column10: portrayed by [[Noah Schnapp]]
column11: is a recurring character in the [[Season 1first season]] of [[Stranger Things]] and a main character in the [[Season 2second season]]. On the night of November 6th
column13: Will was abducted by the [[Demogorgon]] and taken into an alternate dimension dubbed the [[Upside Down]]. For a week
column14: Will evaded the creature while his family and friends desperately searched for him. Although he was eventually rescued and returned to normal life
column15: his time in the Upside Down left him with a mysterious connection to the alternate realm. {{Center[[Will Byers]]}} [[Category:Main Page templates]]|

edit_content: |{{HeadermaintextFEATURED ARTICLEsize30barwidth355}} {{Headermaintext[[The VoidTHE VOID]]size23barwidth0}} [[File:Stranger Things 1x06Elevens mental void.jpgleft200pxlinkThe Void]]The Void is a visual representation of [[Eleven]]s mind while using extrasensory perception to locate other entities in different locations to her own. The Void appears as a vast endless expanse of nothingness. The floor is covered in a thin layer of water. It is completely empty
column10: not including Eleven herself or whatever or whoever she is trying to locate. {{Center[[The Void]]}} [[Category:Main Page templates]]|

edit_content: |{{HeadermaintextFEATURED ARTICLEsize30barwidth355}} {{Headermaintext[[The Vanishing of Will ByersTHE VANISHING OF WILL BYERS]]size23barwidth0}} [[File:The Vanishing of Will Byers S01E01 SS 001.pngleft260pxlinkThe Vanishing of Will Byers]]"Chapter One: The Vanishing of Will Byers" is the first episode of [[Stranger ThingsStranger Things]] and the first episode of the [[Stranger Things/Season 1first season]]. It was written and directed by the [[The Duffer BrothersDuffer Brothers]] and premiered on [[Netflix]] on July 15
column10: 2016 along with the rest of the season. On his way home from a [[Mike Wheelerfriend]]s house
column11: young [[Will ByersWill]] sees [[The Monstersomething terrifying]]. Nearby
column12: a [[Gatesinister secret]] lurks in the depths of a [[Hawkins National Laboratorygovernment lab]]. {{Center[[The Vanishing of Will Byers]]}} [[Category:Main Page templates]]|

column11: the machine fired a highpowered laser beam which could open "a doorway between worlds". {{Center[[The Key]]}} [[Category:Main Page templates]]|

column13: the only appropriate target for a {{TMain}} link in the lead section would be the article itself
column14: which is not useful. Usage ; Basic usage: {{TMainpage}} ; All parameters: page1 page2 page3 ... l1 label1 l2 label2 l3 label3 ... selfref yes Parameters

column17: and links to sections are automatically formatted as page § section
column18: rather than the MediaWiki default of pagesection.

column20: the current page name (with no namespace prefix) is used instead. No errors can be displayed due to the illegal usage of parameters or other usages (i.e. the first parameter can be omitted
column21: other parameters can be used even if the first one is empty (and automatically filled with the current page name (with no namespace prefix))

|While Benny is doing dishes
column10: Eleven is feeding the rottweiler fish. The dog licks her face
column11: causing her to smile. Benny remarks that a smile looks good on her and Eleven calls him good in return. He states he knows a few people who would disagree
column12: and reveals a list of tattooed names on his arm
column13: most likely belonging to his exgirlfriends. Eleven points to a name reading Tommy
column14: saying it belongs to his little brother. Benny is confused
column15: but before he can question further
column16: he hears someone arrive in the driveway. A woman named [[Connie Frazier]] is at the door. After saying she is from Social Services
column17: Benny lets her in. Connie shoots Benny
column18: and agents swarm the restaurant. In the kitchen
column19: Agent One kills the dog when it attempts to attack him. Suddenly
column20: Eleven blasts the storage closet door open injuring the agents in the process. She laments Bennys and the dogs deaths
column22: and then flees. Act Five At the bonfire
column23: Nancy and Barb are waiting for Steve. He finally shows up
column24: but appears to be drunk and stoned. He leads Nancy away
column25: leaving Barb behind. Meanwhile
column26: Mike
column28: and Dustin meet and set off for Mirkwood. Steve leads Nancy to a more secluded part of the beach. He pushes her down and begins removing her clothing. Nancy is hesitant towards Steves advances
column29: but he continues anyway. Back at the bonfire
column30: Barb gets tired of waiting for Nancy and decides to leave. After starting her car
column31: the radio cycles through various stations playing garbled
column32: distorted noise and the cars lights flicker. Confused
column33: Barb turns the engine off. A moment later
column34: the back window shatters
column35: the cars lights turn on
column36: and a highpitched sound is heard. Once the sound has faded and the lights have dimmed
column37: Barb is gone. When Jonathan arrives home
column38: Joyce is working on Wills missing poster. They are consoling each other when the phone rings. Joyce answers it
column39: but only hears the sound of someones breathing. She repeatedly asks who it is
column40: with the breathing only growing louder. At last
column41: a distant voice belonging to Will responds. Joyce frantically asks where he is
column42: but his voice is replaced with a new
column43: inhuman one. A highpitched sound emits from the receiver. Joyce drops the phone
column44: her palm now seared. Jonathan quickly grabs the phone
column45: but the line is now dead. A distant voice calls for help. Barbara stumbles onto the beach
column46: her nose and ears bleeding. The beach is empty but she can still hear the distant sounds of the bonfire. There is a thick fog
column47: and the waves seem to roll in slowly
column48: like time is distorted. There are pulsating growths all over the sand and blue lightning flashes in the sky. Barb hears guttural sounds coming from behind her. She turns to see a horde of shadowed figures heading towards her. The boys are searching for Will on Mirkwood when Mike sees a figure in the middle of the road. He tries to avoid it
column49: causing Lucas and Dustin to crash into him. Once hes back on his feet Mike shines his flashlight on the figure
column50: revealing it to be Eleven. A rumbling sound is heard from overhead
column51: making Mike look up at the sky. Joyce
column53: and Hopper are looking up too. Dark silhouetted clouds roll in above the town
column54: and blue lightning illuminates the sky. The script ends ominously
column55: saying The storm is no longer coming. Its here. }}|

edit_content: |While Benny is doing dishes
column10: Eleven is feeding the rottweiler fish. The dog licks her face
column11: causing her to smile. Benny remarks that a smile looks good on her and Eleven calls him good in return. He states he knows a few people who would disagree
column12: and reveals a list of tattooed names on his arm
column13: most likely belonging to his exgirlfriends. Eleven points to a name reading Tommy
column14: saying it belongs to his little brother. Benny is confused
column15: but before he can question further
column16: he hears someone arrive in the driveway. A woman named [[Connie Frazier]] is at the door. After saying she is from Social Services
column17: Benny lets her in. Connie shoots Benny
column18: and agents swarm the restaurant. In the kitchen
column19: Agent One kills the dog when it attempts to attack him. Suddenly
column20: Eleven blasts the storage closet door open injuring the agents in the process. She laments Bennys and the dogs deaths
column22: and then flees. Act Five At the bonfire
column23: Nancy and Barb are waiting for Steve. He finally shows up
column24: but appears to be drunk and stoned. He leads Nancy away
column25: leaving Barb behind. Meanwhile
column26: Mike
column28: and Dustin meet and set off for Mirkwood. Steve leads Nancy to a more secluded part of the beach. He pushes her down and begins removing her clothing. Nancy is hesitant towards Steves advances
column29: but he continues anyway. Back at the bonfire
column30: Barb gets tired of waiting for Nancy and decides to leave. After starting her car
column31: the radio cycles through various stations playing garbled
column32: distorted noise and the cars lights flicker. Confused
column33: Barb turns the engine off. A moment later
column34: the back window shatters
column35: the cars lights turn on
column36: and a highpitched sound is heard. Once the sound has faded and the lights have dimmed
column37: Barb is gone. When Jonathan arrives home
column38: Joyce is working on Wills missing poster. They are consoling each other when the phone rings. Joyce answers it
column39: but only hears the sound of someones breathing. She repeatedly asks who it is
column40: with the breathing only growing louder. At last
column41: a distant voice belonging to Will responds. Joyce frantically asks where he is
column42: but his voice is replaced with a new
column43: inhuman one. A highpitched sound emits from the receiver. Joyce drops the phone
column44: her palm now seared. Jonathan quickly grabs the phone
column45: but the line is now dead. A distant voice calls for help. Barbara stumbles onto the beach
column46: her nose and ears bleeding. The beach is empty but she can still hear the distant sounds of the bonfire. There is a thick fog
column47: and the waves seem to roll in slowly
column48: like time is distorted. There are pulsating growths all over the sand and blue lightning flashes in the sky. Barb hears guttural sounds coming from behind her. She turns to see a horde of shadowed figures heading towards her. The boys are searching for Will on Mirkwood when Mike sees a figure in the middle of the road. He tries to avoid it
column49: causing Lucas and Dustin to crash into him. Once hes back on his feet Mike shines his flashlight on the figure
column50: revealing it to be Eleven. A rumbling sound is heard from overhead
column51: making Mike look up at the sky. Joyce
column53: and Hopper are looking up too. Dark silhouetted clouds roll in above the town
column54: and blue lightning illuminates the sky. The script ends ominously
column55: saying The storm is no longer coming. Its here. }}|

|[[Stranger Things]] is a televisionformat series created by the [[The Duffer BrothersDuffer Brothers]] released as a [[Netflix]] original series on July 15
column10: 2016. The show takes place in the fictional town of [[Hawkins]]
column11: [[Indiana]] in the earlytomid 1980s. The [[Season 1first season]] revolves around the disappearance of [[Will Byers]]
column12: while the [[Season 2second season explores]] the repercussions of the mysterious events of season 1. The upcoming [[Season 3third season]] will be focusing on "forces of evil that are new." {{clear}}|

edit_content: |{{documentation}}|
|This template is used to create hatnotes to point to a small number of other
column10: related
column11: titles at the top of [[Help:Sectionarticle sections]]. It looks like this: {{see alsoArticle}} Do not use this template inside the "See also" section at the end of an article
column12: or for links to other articles or subsections of the same article within regular article text. Where subsections are linked to
column13: {{TSection link}} may be suitable instead. Refer to the examples below to see how the template handles link targets containing section links and commas. Usage ; Basic usage: &123;{see alsopage1page2page3...}} ; All parameters: &123;{see also page1 page2 page3 ... label 1 label 1 label 2 label2 label 3 label3 ... l1 label1 l2 label2 l3 label3 ... selfref yes category no }} Parameters This template accepts the following parameters:
column14: ... the pages to link to. At least one page name is required. Categories and files are automatically escaped with the [[Help:Colon trickcolon trick]]
column15: and links to sections are automatically formatted as page § section
column16: rather than the MediaWiki default of pagesection.
column17: ...; optional labels for each of the pages to link to. if set to "yes"
column20: adds the CSS class "selfref". This is used to denote selfreferences. if set to "no"
column24: suppresses the error tracking category ([[:Category:Hatnote templates with errors]]). This only has an effect if the first positional parameter (the page to link to) is omitted. Examples → {{see alsoArticle}} → {{see alsoArticleSection}} → {{see alsoArticleSectionlabel 1Custom section label}} → {{see alsoArticle1Article2Article3}} → {{see alsoArticle1Article
column25: 2Article3}} → {{see alsoArticle1l1Custom label 1Article2l2Custom label 2}} → {{See alsoVeni
column26: vidi
column29: viciJulius CaesarCivil war}} → {{See alsoJulius CaesarCivil warVeni
column31: vici}} → {{See alsoJulius CaesarCivil warCrossing the Rubicon}} Errors If no page names are supplied
column32: the template will output the following message: {{see alsocategoryno}} If you see this error message
column33: it is for one of four reasons: No parameters were specified (the template code was instead. Some parameters were specified
column34: but no page names were included. For example
column35: the template text instead. A page name was specified
column36: but it contains an equals sign (""). The equals sign has a special meaning in template code
column37: and because of this it cannot be used in template parameters that do not specify a parameter name. For example
column38: the template code . You tried to access [[Module:See also]] directly by using instead. Pages that contain this error message are tracked in [[:Category:Hatnote templates with errors]]. See also {{tMain}} {{ifeq:{{SUBPAGENAME}}sandbox [[Category:List templates]] [[Category:Exclude in print]] [[Category:Hatnote templates]] [[Category:Relatedtopic templates]] [[Category:Crossreference templates]] }}|

|{{Documentation subpage}} Usage type the type of page to be used. Choices: bio Biography (the "General" or "Summary" tab for the character) dev Development/Wardrobe gameplay Gameplay quotes Quotes appearances Appearances gallery Gallery notes Further notes The template will pick up the main page that it is used on (the "BASEPAGENAME" in the code). For example
column10: if the template is placed on Morpheus D. Duvall/notes
column11: the Basepagename will be Morpheus D. Duvall. This template is based on a similar code from the Simpsons Wiki

edit_content: |{{Headermain text user guidelines size 60 barwidth 450 }} This page outlines the basic guidelines that users must follow while active on the Stranger Things Wiki. Please be aware that in addition to the guidelines on this page
column10: users must also follow Fandom’s [https://www.fandom.com/termsofuse Terms of Use]. Any questions should be directed toward the [[Stranger Things Wiki:Staffwikis staff]]. Basic Guidelines In compliance with the Terms of Use
column11: users must be at least 13 years of age in order to create an account and contribute to this wiki. If you reside in the European Economic Area (excluding the UK)
column12: then you must be at least 16 years old. Always assume good faith. Assume that all edits are made with good intentions even if they are wrong (excluding obvious vandalism). Likewise
column14: please assume that it was for a good reason. If you are not sure
column15: it’s always best to ask. Be Respectful. Users should be civil to one another. Absolutely no sexist
column18: or any other derogatory remarks targeted towards any group of people are permitted. Basically
column19: be a decent human being. Do not engage with trolls. Occasionally
column20: there may be a problem user who will vandalize pages and leave derogatory comments and messages. While it’s understandably tempting to engage with this person
column21: it is preferred that this user is ignored. Undo any vandalism the user may have caused and alert an admin immediately. Profiles and User Content Users are free to customize their profiles as they see fit
column22: as long as the content doesnt conflict with the rules on this page. No sexual or explicit content will be permitted. Fan content is only allowed on user profiles. Before uploading fan content that you did not create yourself
column23: get permission from the original creator. If you have discovered that something you created is being used without your consent
column24: please contact a member of the wikis staff and the file in question will be removed. Any files that break the rules will be deleted without warning. However
column25: the user will be notified that the file was deleted
column26: as well as the reason why. Do NOT edit another users profile without their permission. If a users profile content does not follow these guidelines
column27: please contact an admin. Editing Users are expected to follow the wiki’s editing policies. Please see the [[Stranger Things Wiki:Style GuideStyle Guide]] and [[Stranger Things Wiki:Layout GuideLayout Guide]] for the complete explanation of editing policies. Edits should be constructive and made with the purpose of improving an article’s content. Do not engage in edit wars. Instead
column28: discuss with other users or the wiki’s staff to find a solution. Do NOT vandalize the articles. You will be blocked. You have been warned. Article Comments All comments under an article’s comment section should pertain to that article in some way. Inappropriate comments and comments containing spam will be removed. Discussion Board The Discussion Board’s guidelines can also be found [https://strangerthings.fandom.com/d/g here]. Be nice and treat people with respect. Keep discussions civil and be openminded about differing opinions. Threads and posts that solicit upvotes will be deleted. Offtopic conversations will be deleted. Impersonation of other users or famous people will not be tolerated. If you have been banned and return on a new account
column29: your posts will be deleted and your new account(s) will be banned. No sharing personal information about yourself or other people. No posts about people not involved with Stranger Things. Spamming
column31: or vandalizing of any kind will be deleted and will lead to your account being banned. Posts made with the sole purpose of spreading false information will be deleted. The report feature is for posts and comments that break the guidelines on this page. Do not report posts simply because you dont like them or for having an opinion you dont agree with. [[Category:Templates]]|

column10: for getting into a fight with Mike? Is Lonnie an antagonist
column11: for being a deadbeat? Is Joyces boss an antagonist for almost denying her advances on her paycheck? Is Mr Scotts date an antagonist for giving him the cold shoulder? Maybe Brenner has ends that justify the means. Is the Monster truly an antagonist
column12: or is it just eating to survive? Calling someone an antagonist is purely a subjective moral judgement in some cases. Im not sure its a valid category
column13: and theres definitely not a unifying factor about everyone being called an antagonist here that ties them together
column14: which is kinda the point of a category. [[w:User:FishTankFishTank]] ([[w:Message Wall:FishTankwall]]) 03:07

column10: |Now before you go on Judging me
column11: let me tell you this did not happen overnight. This all took place at the end of 2017 when my brother and I finished watching Stranger Things (both seasons) somewhere in December. After finishing it

edit_content: |This is my Theory for the entire 4th Season In Season 3
column10: we saw Hopper get blown up
column11: Eleven losing her powers and flash forward to October 1985
column12: we see the Byers move out with Eleven somewhere far away with promises of visiting each other on the Holidays. Then jump to Kamchatka
column13: Russia and we see two guards drag a prisoner towards a fully grown Demogorgon
column14: and they also have an American Prisoner. Many have theorized that Hopper is that American Prisoner and some has also theorized that its actually Brenner and Hopper is either dead or stuck in the Upside Down (judging by the ladder near the machine which was on Hoppers side). I personally want to believe all of them (except for Hopper dead theory) and I have theorized how the next Season (Stranger Things 4) might go (which also includes all the theories mentioned above except for Hopper dead theory). Heres how I think El will get back her powers
column15: it will probably happen because of Will. Hear me out
column16: Will got stuck in the Upside Down and had formed a connection with the Mind Flayer because of Eleven; now that Hopper is (supposedly) dead
column17: Joyce took in Eleven in her family and moved far away from Hawkins therefore Eleven and Will will form some kind of brothersister bond. And because of that bond they will have the need to protect each other. If one of the Bullies in their new school thinks (I hope) Will is gay then they would probably get a beating somewhere in front El and she unable to help will feel a strong emotion of anger and sadness and suddenly her powers reawakened. This could also begin with a little hint where El is constantly having dreams of Hopper being in a Russian Prison with Russian Guards or hiding in the Upside Down against the Demogorgon. Of course when she tells Joyce about it
column18: she passes it off as a Nightmare. By the end of first episode she reawakens her power and the first thing she does is to see whether her visions of Hopper were dream or not and surprisingly she finds them to be true. They return to Hawkins after the incident of Elevens power to cool it off and Eleven mentions it to everyone. Thus the entire season will go on finding and Saving Hopper from either the Russian Prison or The Upside Down. If Hopper is in the Upside Down then she might find Brenner in the Russian Prison. What do you think about my ST4 Theory? [[Category:Blog posts]]|

page_title: |User blog:AbdullahBD02/My Theory on how the Russians got their own Demogorgon|
edit_content: |At the end of Season 3 we saw Hopper going off at an explosion. But we didnt see him going off as he disappeared from the machine by the intervals of frames. Then flash forward to 3 months later; October 1985
column10: in Kamchatka
column11: Russia. We see a couple of Russian Guards open a cell to take out a Prisoner for some reason and before one of the guards could open the door
column15: and opened the door right next to that, dragged the prisoner behind that door to somewhere and finally we get a glimpse of Russians very own Demogorgon. But how did they got it? This has something to do with Hopper is alive" theory. Hear me out
column17: when the machine went off and Hopper was on the wrong side of the machine
column18: so he couldnt go back to Joyce and she had no choice but to turn the key to destroy the machine. If you havent noticed
column19: there was a ladder right next to where Hopper was standing. So when Joyce turned the key
column21: climbed down and having no choice went through the portal believing that El will find him. But instead he got stuck in there for The Duffers know how long. Meanwhile the Russians once again tried to open the portal back in Russia and probably succeeded. And from there Hopper got out and Demogorgon was probably chasing him. Thus the Russians caught two birds with one stone. And if youre asking about the 10 feet tall cage Erica found on Episode 6
column22: the Russians probably anticipated that there was some kind of Monsters behind the gate and kept it as Precaution or Brenner. What do you think? [[Category:Blog posts]]|

edit_content: |This is my review to the crtically acclaim Stranger Things 2/ Stranger Things Season 2: Stranger Things 2 has definitely upped both the horifying aspect and the scale from the 1st season and is fittingly a massive improvement. It has features some fantastic character development to most kids who were a bit left out in Season 1. The Duffer Brothers have done a great job giving Noah Schnapp the role of Will as he is still suffering from the consequences of the Demogorgon and the way he shows his fear and pain is really fascinating. Millie Bobby Brown and David Harbour as Eleven and Jim Hopper respectively has also acted really well
column10: portraying the dynamic bond the duo made as they face newer challenges from the beginning. The VFX team has also added a lot of visual aspects that make the atmosphere of Hawkins and the creatures look more alive as well as frightening. Its just the definitive sequel one can only hope from such a TV series. And thats without saying how the final act of the last episode "The Gate" was so charming (most memorable scene)
column11: which without spoiling
column12: is hard to explain. Though Season 2 has been superb
column13: it is not completely flawless at few aspects. Because the episode "The Lost Sister" broke the pace and tension a bit
column14: that rose from the previous episode "The Spy" as it mostly focuses on Eleven and her unexpected journey. Overall
column15: I would highly recommend any Stranger Things fan to watch it as it is both heartbreaking and also very memorable! My overall rating: 9.5/10 [[File:Mike_is_surprised_to_see_Eleven.pngthumbleft196px]] In any case
column16: this is just my review from my perspective. And so
column17: sound off your opinions in the comments below. [[Category:Blog posts]]|
